`crates/steno/src` is the compiler crate root: source `.steno` text goes in, Plover dictionaries / LSP snippets / block-editor keystrokes / viz JSON come out. `lib.rs` defines and wires the pipeline; every other item here is either a pipeline stage, a shared type layer used by multiple stages, or a binary consumer in `bin/`.

The pipeline is strictly forward and stage-typed: `parse/` → `Vec<Entry>` (with `Chunk`/`Expr`/`EntryFlags`) → `expand/` → `TypedEntry` (four sub-passes, terminal-flag fixup order matters) → `render/` (Plover dict text, profile-forked plain/smart) and `snippet/` (LSP bodies) in parallel off the same `TypedEntry`, using the same terminal/non-terminal split independently in each. `stroke/` underlies both parse (stroke key parsing) and render/expand (count-bank merging), and `editor/` underlies both `render/` (keystroke interpretation) and `blocks.rs` (auto-indent-aware event emission for `@literal` templates) — both consumers pattern-match `editor::Event`'s exact three-variant shape, so adding a variant means auditing both. `error.rs` supplies one error type per stage, all `Result`-based, no panics anywhere in the crate; `json_out.rs` is the shared serializer that must byte-match TS's `JSON.stringify` output, consumed by both `render/`'s dict-building and `snippet/`'s `build.rs`.

Cross-cutting invariant: `terminal` flags are set once by `expand/`'s family-fixup pass and never flipped afterward; `render/` and `snippet/` both trust that flag for their profile/routing forks without re-deriving it. Stroke text is always canonically re-sorted by `stroke/`'s `render_stroke`, so no downstream code should assume string-identity round-tripping of stroke text.

`bin/` binaries are the only I/O boundary — library code here never writes files; each binary calls a different combination of `expand_dict`/render/snippet functions to produce one artifact.